metadata.name: Statue of Liberty
metadata.description: Gifted by France to the United States in 1886, the Statue of Liberty stands at 305 feet from the ground to the tip of the torch and is an iconic symbol of freedom and democracy. This colossal neoclassical sculpture on Liberty Island in New York Harbor welcomes visitors from around the globe.

metadata.name: Three WTC
metadata.description: Part of the new World Trade Center complex, Three World Trade Center features a height of 1,079 feet and offers a striking glass façade. Completed in 2018, it contributes to the revitalization of Lower Manhattan and stands as a testament to modern architectural design.

metadata.name: One WTC
metadata.description: Also known as the Freedom Tower. As the main building of the rebuilt World Trade Center complex, One World Trade Center soars to a patriotic height of 1,776 feet - the year of the declaration of independence - making it the tallest building in the Western Hemisphere. Completed in 2014, it's a symbol of resilience and renewal after the events of September 11, 2001.

metadata.name: NY Life Building
metadata.description: With its distinctive gilded spire, the New York Life Building is a classic example of the Gothic Revival skyscraper and stretches up to 615 feet. Completed in 1928, it remains a key feature of the Madison Square Park skyline.

metadata.name: Guggenheim Museum
metadata.description: Designed by Frank Lloyd Wright and completed in 1959, the Guggenheim Museum is not only a repository of modern art but also an architectural landmark. Its unique spiral design and inverted-ziggurat exterior stand out in Manhattan's Upper East Side.

metadata.name: Empire State Building
metadata.description: An enduring symbol of New York City, the Empire State Building reaches 1,454 feet with its antenna and held the title of the world's tallest building for nearly 40 years after its completion in 1931, and again after 9/11. This Art Deco masterpiece is a staple of the city's tourist attractions and offers sweeping panoramic views from its observatories.

metadata.name: Conde Nast Building
metadata.description: Also knows as 4 Times Square, the tower is known as a pioneer in green building practices, the Conde Nast Building stands at 809 feet and was completed in 1999. Its prominent location at Times Square and the use of an LED display for Nasdaq gives it a unique presence in the city.

metadata.name: Chrysler Building
metadata.description: An iconic example of Art Deco architecture, the Chrysler Building was the tallest in the world upon its completion in 1930, reaching 1,046 feet. Its gleaming stainless steel crown and spire remain a distinctive element in the cityscape.

metadata.name: Washington Square Arch
metadata.description: Built in 1892 to celebrate the centennial of George Washington's inauguration, the Washington Square Arch is a marble Roman triumphal arch that stands 77 feet tall. It is a historic landmark and a focal point of Washington Square Park, a hub for artists, students, and activists.

metadata.name: Bank of America Tower
metadata.description: This skyscraper boasts a pinnacle height of 1,200 feet, making it one of the most prominent on the NYC skyline and is renowned for its environmentally sustainable design. Completed in 2009, it's not only a visual marvel but also one of the most ecologically friendly buildings, earning a platinum LEED certification.

metadata.name: NYC
metadata.description: New York City, also known as 'The City That Never Sleeps,' is a bustling metropolis and the largest city in the United States, known for its iconic skyline, diverse cultures, vibrant arts scene, world-renowned cuisine, and being a hub of finance, media, and commerce, with numerous iconic landmarks such as the Statue of Liberty and the Empire State Building.

metadata.name: Tzameret Towers
metadata.description: Tzameret Towers, completed in 2005 in Tel Aviv, consist of luxury residential skyscrapers known for their sleek design and prominence in the city's skyline.

metadata.name: Liverpool Cathedral
metadata.description: Liverpool Cathedral, completed in 1978, is one of the largest Anglican cathedrals in the world, renowned for its grand Gothic Revival architecture.

metadata.name: Isbank Tower
metadata.description: Isbank Tower, completed in 2000, is a prominent feature of Istanbul's skyline, known for its modern design and status as one of Turkey’s tallest buildings.

metadata.name: Tsing Ma Bridge
metadata.description: Tsing Ma Bridge, completed in 1997 in Hong Kong, is one of the world’s longest suspension bridges, crucial for road and rail traffic.

metadata.name: Hatch Memorial Shell
metadata.description: The Hatch Memorial Shell, located in Boston, completed in 1941, is an outdoor concert venue known for its half-dome structure facing the Charles River.

metadata.name: Rock and Roll Hall of Fame

metadata.name: Main Tower

metadata.name: Manchester Grand Hyatt Hotel

metadata.name: Burj Al Arab

metadata.name: Battersea Power Station

metadata.name: Wells Fargo Center

metadata.name: U.S. Bancorp Tower
